                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d181">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.24/1082: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Leahy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Vichy</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-06-10T19:00:00+02:00"
                            >June 10, 1941—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 11—8:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>666. Department’s telegram 440, May 28, 7 p.m., concerning Japanese seizures of
                    American goods in Indochina.</p>
                <p>Chauvel said this afternoon that he had telegraphed to Hanoi to ascertain the
                    facts before replying to the Embassy’s note. He said: “Frankly we were not in a
                    position as a practical question to prevent the Japanese from taking these
                    goods; however, if their seizure was carried out with the connivance or under
                    the pressure of any French authorities in Indochina it was contrary to explicit
                    instructions. We certainly did not wish to be a party to any such attempt
                    against which we ourselves have vigorously protested both before and after the
                    seizure.”</p>
                <p>Chauvel added that he has had practically no news of interest on the Far East for
                    some days, particularly no indication as to Japan’s <pb facs="0186" n="176"
                        xml:id="pg_176"/> future policies. He confirmed reports that the Russians
                    are apparently keeping the Chinese well supplied with arms and munitions.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Leahy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
